post_text: Debut episode of the new show called "Stafford Pride" coming this Monday, September 7 about the life of our Mayor Scarcella!
shared_text:
Stafford Pride Episode 1 Tribute to Mayor Leonard Scarcella

City of Stafford premiered a video.
September 3 at 9:53 AM ·

'Stafford Pride' is a new program series highlighting the best things about Stafford, Texas. This debut episode explores the life, accomplishments, and legacy of longtime Stafford Mayor, Leonard Scarcella. He and the city grew together from humble beginnings to a stature like no other. Scarcella was the Mayor of Stafford, Texas for over 50 years, but recently lost his battle with cancer on June 28, 2020. This show is dedicated as a tribute to Scarcella and the legacy he left behind. Watch to see what makes him, and Stafford, so special!

post_text:
CONGRATULATIONS CLASS OF 2020!

Our Graduation Day was definitely not how any of us imagined it would be, but we had 192 out of 260 graduating Seniors come out yesterday to obtain their diploma. Some came from work, some came after class and others came with their family, but all came with Spartan Pride. A special coincidence about Graduation Day is that our last student that arrived to walk, Kevin Zuniga Gutierrez, would have also been the last Senior to walk in a traditional ceremony.

We had over 100 volunteers for this event who wouldn’t miss cheering on these students, and we are grateful to everyone who participated. If you missed the event, please check with the high school front office starting next Monday, July 20 to pick up your diplomas.

post_text: The deadline to apply for P-EBT food benefits has been extended to July 31. Did your child receive free or reduced-price school meals through the National School Lunch Program during the 2019-2020 school year? If so, your family may be eligible for this one-time food benefit. Visit hhs.texas.gov/pebt to learn more about P-EBT. For questions regarding eligibility or if you need help applying, contact the P-EBT Call Center at 833-613-6220. The public charge rule does not apply to P-EBT benefits.

post_text:
What are the plans for next school year?

Our campuses will be closed on Fri 6/26 and re-open on Mon 7/13 to provide our staff time to recharge. As we welcome students back on campus in 2020-21, we will continue to seek guidance from the Texas Education Agency and local officials. The week of our re-open, we will share our safety protocols and learning plans for next school year, especially as we prepare to become a 1:1 campus of students to devices.

It's important for you to know, as we move forward, providing a safe environment and quality education are essential to us and will remain our first priority.

What are the plans for next school year?

The week of our re-open, we will share our safety protocols and learning plans for next school year, especially as we prepare to become a 1:1 campus of students to devices.

It's important for you to know, as we move forward, providing a safe environment and quality education are essential to us and will remain our first priority.

REMINDER: At the end of every school year, it's important to measure the progress of our students by identifying strengths and recognizing weaknesses in order to close educational gaps. The deadline for submitting the End of Year Assessment is coming up and although it is not required, the test will help us and your students. Students can take this assessment at home at their own pace and can complete it in a few hours. Upon completion, immediate results will be available for parents and students. In order to get your login information and any other accommodations, please contact the individuals listed below.

Who: Students in grades 3-11
When: Now through June 12 at 5:00 PM
Where: Online at tx.schoolnet.com
What's Needed: User, PW and Test Code
Contact: Sherri Hobbs (shobbs@staffordmsd.org) for 3rd-6th grade or Jerrae Bazile (jbazile@staffordmsd.org) for 7th-11th grade

post_text:
NEW DISTRICT COMMUNICATIONS & MARKETING COORDINATOR:

Hi Spartans! My name is Gracie Martinez and I am a former student of SMSD and happy to return as a staff member nearly 25 years after my education first began on campus. Prior to joining the team, I worked at a successful holding company directly supporting the CEO and rebranding an entire agency. I graduated from the University of Houston with a BA in Public Relations as valedictorian and a Terry Scholar. As I step into Michael Sudhalter's position, I look forward to honoring the initiatives he had in place as well as continuing to create new ones. Even though school has changed quite a bit these days, my passion for higher education and purposed conversation has me feeling like I'm at the right place at the right time.

In my free time, I like watching Disney movies with Spanish subtitles on and I like to eat Best Burger once a week to keep the doctors away. I can't wait to meet more of you soon.

GO SPARTANS!

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit:

https://hhs.texas.gov/services/health/coronavirus-covid-19/coronavirus-covid-19-information-texans/pandemic-ebt-p-ebt-due-covid-19

post_text:
Greetings SMSD Parents & Students!

To measure student progress during the 2019-2020 school year, Stafford MSD will be administering an End-of-Year assessment. This assessment is designed by the Texas Education Agency to determine student growth and understanding of the state curriculum. Test results will not be used for course grading or promotion purposes; rather, the End-of-Year assessment will give parents and educators a powerful tool that shows what their students have learned and where they can improve their knowledge and understanding of key subject matters heading into the 2020-21 academic year. This information will help develop instructional plans that use the identified strengths and weaknesses to close educational gaps and push towards content mastery.

Please see attached for additional information.

✏️ STAAR TESTING ✏️

In response to the outpour of questions during our recent Town Hall Meeting concerning STAAR, we would like to inform you that The State has waived all academic assessment requirements for the remainder of the 2019–2020 school year. This includes all STAAR assessments including tests for grades 3-8, End-of-Course (EOC) Assessments, and STAAR Alternate 2 tests.

For more information, please visit:

https://tea.texas.gov/about-tea/news-and-multimedia/correspondence/taa-letters/cancellation-of-staar-testing-for-the-remainder-of-the-school-year

EXCITING NEWS! DIGITAL FLYER DELIVERY STARTS APRIL 15, 2020!

In an effort to provide increased access to programs and resources that improve the trajectory of our students' lives, Stafford Municipal School District is preparing to launch Peachjar. This new platform will enable us to send important school and approved after school flyers to parents digitally, saving our schools time, money, and paper.

School-approved digital flyers will be sent to your email inbox where you can easily click to sign up for events and programs.

Please see attached for more details.

April 11, 2020 TEA Update:

The virus lives in tiny droplets in the lungs of people w/ COVID-19, even when they don’t show symptoms. We can breathe the same air as anyone within abt. 6 ft. of us. Staying farther apart from people during this time reduces the chance of breathing in the virus. #StayHomeTexas

Spanish:

El virus vive en gotas en los pulmones de personas con COVID-19, y a veces no tienen síntomas. Puedes respirar el mismo aire que cualquiera a 6 pies de ti. Mantente más alejado de las personas durante este tiempo para reducir la posibilidad de respirar el virus. #StayHomeTexas

April 10, 2020 TEA Update:

Coughing & sneezing can send tiny infected droplets into the air which can be inhaled by anyone within 6 feet of us. Always cough or sneeze into a tissue or your elbow and immediately wash your hands to lessen the risk of spreading the virus. Be smart. Stay well! #StayHomeTexas

Spanish:

Toser y estornudar puede llevar gotas infectadas al aire, que pueden ser inhaladas por personas que estén a 6 pies de ti. Siempre tosa o estornude en pañuelos desechables o en el codo y lávese las manos para disminuir la propagación del virus. ¡Mantente sano! #StayHomeTexas

People with no symptoms have the potential to unknowingly spread COVID-19! That’s why it’s best for everyone in your family to stay at home and away from others as much as possible until instructed otherwise from state and local officials. #StayHomeTexas

April 6, 2020 TEA Update:

English:

Common symptoms of #COVID19 are fever, dry cough, & shortness of breath. If you have mild symptoms, call your doctor & #StayHome. If you develop serious symptoms, such as trouble breathing, pressure in the chest, or bluish lips or face, call your doctor & seek care immediately.

Spanish:

Los síntomas comunes de #COVID19 son fiebre, tos seca y dificultad para respirar. Si tiene síntomas leves, llame a su médico y quedate en casa.Si desarrolla síntomas graves, como dificultad para respirar o presión en el pecho, busque atención médica de inmediato. #StayHome

April 5, 2020 TEA Update:

English:

Before social distancing, each person with #COVID19 spread the virus to 2.5 more people. At that pace, most would get it, and many more people would die. But we can slow the spread. That’s why we all #StayHome. #ApartTogether we slow coronavirus.

Spanish:

Antes del distanciamiento social, cada persona con #COVID19 transmitió el virus a 2.5 personas. A ese ritmo, muchas personas se contagiarían, y muchas personas morirían. Pero podemos retrasar la propagación. Por eso todos quedemonos en casa y paremos el Coronavirus. #ApartTogether

post_text:
Stafford MSD families,

We are pleased to announce that the District will begin processing and loaning a limited number of laptop computers and iPADS as early as next week.

Please note - families will only be able to receive one device per family. Please go to https://forms.gle/RaNkUTZJUkofqZS8A to register for a device. This form can also be completed on your smartphone. Registration is required. The district will contact you to let you know if you will receive a device and provide you with the date, time, and location for your laptop pickup.

We hope the devices will assist many of our students who need technology support with the successful completion of online assignments.

Hello, loyal Stafford MSD Facebook Followers!

It has been my distinct honor to maintain the Stafford MSD Facebook Page for the past four years. Today is my final day with the District, as I have accepted an opportunity outside of the Houston Metropolitan area.

I remember starting the page in March 2016 immediately after a Stafford Spartan Soccer Game.

The page recently reached 4,880 followers. Not because of me, but because of the dedicated students, faculty and staff of Stafford Municipal School District. I was simply relaying the message.

I would like to thank SMSD Superintendent Dr. Robert Bostic, SMSD Chief of Innovation & Operation Marva Rasberry and the SMSD Board of Trustees for giving me the opportunity to work on your behalf.

I know Stafford MSD will continue to do excellent things, and I look forward to watching it as a person who follows this page.

Sincerely,

Michael Sudhalter
Communications Coordinator
Stafford Municipal School District

post_text:
Stafford MSD will partner with the Missouri City-Sugar Land Chapter of Jack and Jill of America incorporated to present
"A Carnival of Beautiful Minds”.

This one-day event, hosted on Friday, Feb. 21 will help address the need for mental health awareness and outreach in the Stafford community.

The MCSL chapter worked with Marva Rasberry, Chief of Innovation & Operations, to create this program and have received funding for the event through a grant award from the Jack and Jill of America Foundation, Incorporated. Services and support will also be provided by Texas Children’s Hospital.

This project will consist of a mental health fair, which will incorporate a fun carnival theme designed to bring awareness and information to middle and high school students. Students will have the opportunity to visit several health-related stations.

Raising awareness on the topic of mental health is indeed a critical need for our youth. We believe “A Carnival of Beautiful Minds” will resonate with your students and have a positive influence on them.

post_text:
"EVERYTHING IS UNDER CONTROL" AT STAFFORD MSD

At 8 a.m. this morning, a construction contractor inadvertently ruptured a Centerpoint gas line, adjacent to Stafford MSD Property, while working on a sidewalk.

Stafford MSD is closed today in observance of President's Day, so students and most of our employees are not on campus.

As a precaution, the Stafford Fire Department enacted a Shelter in Place for one street near the Intermediate Campus. Centerpoint employees came out and fixed the line, and thus the Shelter In Place was lifted at 10:30 a.m.

According to Stafford Fire Chief Larry DiCamillo, "Everything is under control."

Stafford Fire immediately contacted Fort Bend Emergency Medical Services (EMS), and together they determined minimal to no risk for the immediate area, because the line in question was natural gas.

The Shelter in Place did not affect the majority of the Stafford MSD Campus. It only affected the immediate area near the Intermediate Campus.

The District expects to open as scheduled on Tuesday, February 18.

"EVERYTHING IS UNDER CONTROL" AT STAFFORD MSD

At 8 a.m. this morning, a construction contractor inadvertently ruptured a Centerpoint gas line, adjacent to Stafford MSD Property, while working on a sidewalk.

Stafford MSD is closed today in observance of President's Day, so students and most of our employees are not on campus.

As a precaution, the Stafford Fire Department enacted a Shelter in Place for one street near the Intermediate Campus. Centerpoint employees came out and fixed the line, and thus the Shelter In Place was lifted at 10:30 a.m.

According to Stafford Fire Chief Larry DiCamillo, "Everything is under control."

Stafford Fire immediately contacted Fort Bend Emergency Medical Services (EMS), and together they determined minimal to no risk for the immediate area, because the line in question was natural gas.

The Shelter in Place did not affect the majority of the Stafford MSD Campus. It only affected the immediate area near the Intermediate Campus.

The District expects to open as scheduled on Tuesday, February 18.

Stafford MSD Board President Christopher Caldwell started a new tradition at Monday's Board Meeting by presenting the First Annual President's Award in Educational Excellence.

The inaugural honoree was Dr. Rep. Alma Allen, who has proudly served in the Texas House of Representatives since 2004.

Dr. Rep. Allen has 39 years of experience as a professional educator and previously served on the Texas State Board of Education.

Stafford MSD was proud to welcome Dr. Rep. Allen and her family members to Monday's Board of Trustees Meeting.

We thank Dr. Rep. Allen for her commitment to Public Education, here in Stafford and throughout the State of Texas.

Sherri Hobbs taught Kindergarten for 28 years, including 20 years in Stafford.

Almost a decade ago, she decided to earn a Master’s Degree in Counseling from the University of St. Thomas.

“As a teacher, I saw such a need for it, to help students with what they’re dealing with in their lives,” Hobbs said. “I wanted to have a larger impact with more students.”

Hobbs is in her third year as a School Counselor at Stafford Elementary.

“I love going into the classroom to talk to students about good character traits,” Hobbs said. “The kids are the best part of the job. They make my day.”

A Stafford citizen, Hobbs is the proud parent of two Stafford MSD Graduates. She’s also the President of the Stafford Band Boosters – a position she has held for the past 13 years.

“Stafford is my heart,” Hobbs said.

#StaffordMSDProud #CommittedtoSMSD #CounselorAppreciationWeek

STAFFORD MSD ALUMNI UPDATE

Andrea White is a proud Stafford MSD Class of 1997 Graduate.
Two years ago, she was proud to return to the District as a High School Counselor
"I had the opportunity to come back and help the people who raised me," said White, who attended SMSD from Kindergarten through graduation.
White was a standout athlete for Stafford, competing in volleyball, basketball and softball.
"It's been a lot of fun to see how the District has changed and how it's still the same," White said. "The District itself has grown. The students have so many more opportunities than we did 20+ years ago. The heart of the community is still the same, with a small town family atmosphere."
White earned a Master's Degree from Houston Baptist University in Education/Counseling.

#StaffordMSDProud #StaffordAlumni #CounselorAppreciationWeek #CommittedtoSMSD

Today is the first day of #CounselorAppreciationWeek
Stafford High School Lead Counselor Grace Landry has worked for Stafford MSD since 2007. Prior to that, she was a teacher and worked in law enforcement.
“Counselor Appreciation Week means a lot to be appreciated for the work that we do,” Landry said. “It’s a very demanding job.”
School Counselors work with students on academics and guide them through academics, scheduling, testing as well as personal issues that they may face at home or in school.
Landry earned both athletic and academic scholarships to Mississippi Valley State where she studied Criminal Justice and competed in basketball and volleyball. One of herMVSU classmates was Jerry Rice.
Upon moving to the Houston area in the late 1980s, Landry earned two Masters Degrees from Prairie View A&M in Counseling and Human Services, respectively.

She taught many of the original students in SMSD, and this August, she will proudly watch sixth through eighth graders walk into the new Stafford Middle School.

post_text:
STAFFORD MSD TEACHER SPOTLIGHT

It takes a leap of faith to pack everything you own and drive 24 hours to a new place.
But that’s what Stafford Elementary Kindergarten Teacher Kimberly Solomon did six years ago. Shortly after moving from her hometown of Cleveland, Ohio to the Houston area, she discovered Stafford MSD.
“I love Stafford,” Solomon said. “It’s a tight-knit community. We know all of the administrators, and the Superintendent is always around.”
Solomon, a graduate of the University of Findlay in Ohio, was named the Stafford Elementary Teacher of the Month for January.
“It’s a really big honor,” Solomon said. “It validates that the principals have confidence in me.”
If you see Ms. Solomon, be sure to congratulate her, and also wish her a Happy Birthday!

post_text:
Joe Longoria is the third-longest serving Trustee in Stafford MSD Board History. He served from 1985-91 and 1993-02.

Longoria was Board Secretary from 1993-2001 (he was the first Hispanic to serve in that position) and Board Vice President from 2001-02.

In addition, he became the first SMSD Trustee to become a Texas Association of School Boards (TASB) Master Trustee - a feat achieved by three Trustees since -- Mary Jo VonFeldt, Doris Rome, and most recently, by current SMSD Board Vice President Xavier Herrera.

Longoria is a past president of the Gulf Coast Association of School Boards and a past member of both the Mexican American School Board Association, and the TASB Board of Directors.

In addition, he serves on the SMSD Bond Oversight Committee.

#StaffordMSDProud #BoardRecognitionMonth

The late, great James Ratcliff was the longest serving Stafford MSD Board President.

Ratcliff, who had previously worked as a Stafford High School teacher and coach, served as Board President from 1991-2000 (which was his entire tenure on the Board).

There is currently a Stafford MSD Education Foundation Scholarship in his honor, which was presented last spring to Stafford High Class of 2019 Valedictorian Paul Phung.

Ratcliff's widow, Kathy, is still very involved in the District, as a member of both the Bond Oversight Committee and the SMSD Education Foundation Board.

One of the most heartfelt moments in recent Stafford MSD Board History took place on Monday night.

Stafford MSD Trustee Ash Hamirani, who was elected last May, invited Keisha Smith, his Speech/Communications Teacher, to Monday's Board Meeting.

Hamirani, a graduate of Hightower High, took Smith's class in the summer of 2007. They hadn't seen one another in many years. But when Hamirani completed that class in 2007, Smith wrote an encouraging note that Hamirani keeps close by, even to this day.

On Monday night, Hamirani read that note during the Board Meeting and publicly thanked his former teacher for her positive impact on his career and life.

The late, great Margaret Havens made Stafford MSD Board History when she became the first female Board Vice President in District History (1987-88). Since then, four women have served in that position, most recently Virginia Rosas in 2013-14.

Havens, the mother of Stafford Mayor Leonard Scarcella, played an important role in the creation of Stafford MSD. The Stafford Library is named in her honor.

In 2003, Azalia Tennis became the first female Board President in SMSD History. She served until 2007. Cindy Hoelscher became the second female Board President, serving from 2009-11.

There were three female members on the inaugural SMSD Board in 1977 -- Billie Gail Cash, Sophie Salinas and the late Williane Elliott. Elliott was the first Board Secretary in District History, serving from 1982-85.

The National Weather Service is predicting severe weather and strong winds, which will likely begin between 10 p.m. Friday and 1 a.m. Saturday.

While this forecast will not affect daily school operations, the District is taking strong measures to ensure student and staff safety.

We are closely monitoring any changes in the forecast, which would require the District to dismiss school early. While that is unlikely, we are prepared to do so, if necessary.

We have already moved up tonight’s Boys/Girls road basketball games to the late afternoon/early evening, so the return trip from Needville will not coincide with the inclement weather.

We will cancel after-school and school-sponsored weekend events accordingly.

We encourage everyone to stay at home and pay close attention to the weather forecast.

Happy Birthday to Stafford MSD Board Vice President Xavier Herrera!

Herrera was first elected to the Stafford MSD Board in 2015. He is the father of two SMSD graduates and a current Stafford High student.

Herrera is on the Mexican American School Boards Association (MASBA) Board. He is also a Texas Association of School Boards (TASB) Master Trustee.

He is one of only four SMSD Trustees to have served as both Board Secretary (2016-18) and Vice President (2018-present), joining his current Board colleague Greg Holsapple, as well as former SMSD Trustees Joe Longoria and Virginia Rosas.

The answer to the Board Trivia question is current Trustee Greg Holsapple.

Holsapple was Board President from 2007-09, and Vice President from 2003-05, 2006-07, 2009-11 and 2014-15. He served as Board Secretary from 2005-06, 2012-14 and 2015-16.

Holsapple was first elected to the Board in 1991 and served until 1998. He was elected in 2003 and has served since that point. With 24 total years, he's the longest-serving Trustee in SMSD History and the only Trustee with more than 20 years on the Board.

Last month, Wooten signed a letter of intent with Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University Football Team, better known to most of us as Virginia Tech.

post_text:
The Stafford High Boys Basketball Team won its 25-4A District Opener, 78-76 over Fulshear in an overtime thriller on Friday afternoon at the SHS Competition Gym. Stafford overcame an 8-point halftime deficit (38-30).

The Spartans will play a non-district game on Tuesday at Bay City and resume district play with a trip to defending 25-4A champion, Needville, next Friday.

Raul Rodriguez scored two goals and had an assist as the Stafford High Boys Soccer Team defeated West Columbia, 6-0, in the Spartan Cup Semifinals at Spartan Stadium this morning.

The Spartans will face Huffman-Hargrave in the Spartan Cup Championship Game at 3 p.m. tomorrow (Saturday, January 4).

Stafford (2-0) has outscored its first two opponents, 14-1, including an 8-1 victory over Class 5A Fort Bend Marshall yesterday.

post_text:
We were glad to see Stafford MSD Class of 2019 Graduate Zachary Natt on campus this morning.

Natt is a freshman at University of Mary Hardin-Baylor where he is studying Engineering.

He's also a member of the UMHB Football Team that reached the NCAA Division III Quarterfinals. Natt successfully made the move from defensive line (which he played in high school) to offensive line.

It will be the Lady Spartans' first home game since Dec. 20 and an opportunity to win their first district game of the season.

Last season, the SHS Girls Basketball Team swept Fulshear.

It's Stafford MSD Week in New Orleans!

Four days after the Stafford High Mighty Spartans Marching Band performs at the Sugar Bowl (Wednesday, January 1), proud Stafford MSD Class of 2006 graduate Craig Robertson, a New Orleans Saints linebacker, and his teammates will host the Minnesota Vikings in an NFC Wild Card Game (Sunday, January 5)

Robertson finished with four tackles in yesterday's regular season finale victory at Carolina.
